\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Homography is a transformation of coordinates from one image to another,
 normally expressed in a 3√ó3 matrix.
 Its many practical applications include image rectification, stitching,
 and estimation of camera motion, which can be used for robot navigation
 (e.g.
 monocular SLAM).
 Estimating this homography matrix is one of the fundamental problems in
 computer vision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classical feature-based approaches to homography estimation consists of
 a two-stage process: feature point detection and homography estimation.
 Feature points are extracted by using a feature detector such as Scale
 Invariant Feature Transform (SIFT), or Oriented FAST and Rotated BRIEF
 (ORB).
 Due to the limitations of current hand-engineered feature detectors (e.g.
 presence of outliers), an overcomplete set of feature points is extracted
 and used in the next stage.
 Robust homography estimation is then performed by employing the Random
 Sample Consensus (RANSAC) algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent breakthroughs in computer vision were mainly driven by rapid advances
 in deep learning.
 Image classification, object detection, and semantic segmentation are some
 of the tasks in which deep learning models achieve state-of-the-art performance
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "krizhevsky2012imagenet,he2016deep,girshick2014rich,ren2015faster,long2015fully"

\end_inset

.
 More recently, deep learning models have also been developed for homography
 estimation.
 DeTone et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "detone2016deep"

\end_inset

 demonstrated and pioneered the use of the four-point homography parameterizatio
n 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "baker2006parameterizing"

\end_inset

 in a deep learning model.
 Nguyen and Chen et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nguyen2018unsupervised"

\end_inset

 extended the work of DeTone et al.
 by employing a Spatial Transformer Network (STN) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jaderberg2015spatial"

\end_inset

 to make the training self-supervised, thereby allowing the model to be
 used in a wider context.
 Both prior work used VGGNet 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "simonyan2014very"

\end_inset

 as the backbone CNN for feature detection, and dense layers for the regression
 of the homography parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we further improve the homography estimation model by using
 a lightweight backbone CNN (MobileNet 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "howard2017mobilenets"

\end_inset

) and making the model fully convolutional, thereby allowing our model to
 be used in embedded applications.
 A fully convolutional network (FCN) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "long2015fully"

\end_inset

 makes more sense in this case because convolutional layers preserve spatial
 context, which are lost when dense layers are used (because the feature
 maps need to be flattened).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize, our key contributions are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Reduced model footprint in terms of number of parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Demonstrate the effectiveness of FCNs in homography estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We implement our model in Keras 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chollet2015keras"

\end_inset

 using its Tensorflow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "abadi2016tensorflow"

\end_inset

 backend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Related Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we focus only on the reent deep learning work on homography
 estimation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DeTone et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "detone2016deep"

\end_inset

 proposed a supervised deep learning model for estimating the homography
 given a pair of 128√ó128 images.
 They demonstrated the feasibility of using the 4-point parameterization
 of the homography 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "baker2006parameterizing"

\end_inset

 in training both a regression-based and a classification-based estimator.
 Since there are no publicly available datasets for homography estimation,
 they also proposed a method for generating a synthetic dataset for homography
 estimation.
 Their results show that the deep learning model outperformed the classical
 approaches by a significant margin.
 However, their model, which is based on VGGNet, use 34 million parameters
 which can be too large for embedded applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nguyen and Chen et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nguyen2018unsupervised"

\end_inset

 extended the work of DeTone et al.
 by making the training self-supervised, i.e.
 the ground truth homography is not used in training the model.
 They created a customized Spatial Transformer Network 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jaderberg2015spatial"

\end_inset

 which accepts the estimated homography to reproject the first image onto
 the second one which allowed them to use a pixel-wise photometric (L1)
 loss function in training the model.
 The authors focused on making the training self-supervised and did not
 improve upon the original model.
 The choice of loss function (L1) also seem inadequate, thus in this work,
 we propose to use a combination of L2 and Structural Dissimilarity (DSSIM)
 losses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nowruzi et al.
 proposed a hierarchical siamese network for estimating the homography 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nowruzihomography"

\end_inset

.
 The two input images each indepedently flow through a siamese network,
 then are merged together at some point before going through another series
 of convolutions.
 The homography estimate is iteratively refined at each level of the hierarchy.
 While their approach is sound, we argue that we can come up with a faster,
 more efficient model if we process the two images together, like in the
 original approach of DeTone et al.
 Thus, in this work, we leverage the MobileNet architecture which makes
 extensive use of Depthwise Separable Convolutions, making the convolutions
 more parameter-efficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dataset
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We follow the method of DeTone et al.
 for dataset generation and use the same parameters as well.
 That is, all images are scaled to 320√ó240 pixels and are converted to grayscale.
 128√ó128 pixel patches are used, and the corner offset is sampled from a
 uniform distribution of [-32, 32] pixels.
 We use images from the COCO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lin2014microsoft"

\end_inset

 2017 
\shape italic
test
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
val
\shape default
 datasets to generate 12 samples per image, resulting in 550,000 samples
 total.
 We use 500,000 samples for training and set aside the remaining 50,000
 samples for both validation and testing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homography Estimation Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename model-overview.png
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Two-128x128-pixel"

\end_inset

Two 128√ó128 pixel grayscale images are stacked together channel-wise to
 produce the 128√ó128√ó2 input to the model.
 The output is the 4-point parameterized homography.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our proposed homography estimation model is fully convolutional and is based
 on the MobileNet architecture.
 It uses the same inputs and produces the same outputs as the original model
 proposed by DeTone et al., as seen in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Two-128x128-pixel"

\end_inset

.
 Given an image pair 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{A}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{B}(x)$
\end_inset

, the goal of our network model is to output the 
\begin_inset Formula $ƒ§_{4pt}$
\end_inset

 that defines the homography transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $‚Ñã(x_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by cropping two patches 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{B}$
\end_inset

 of size 128√ó128 pixels from the image pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{B}$
\end_inset

 respectively, and using these as inputs to our model.
 The listing in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Model-layers"

\end_inset

 shows the layer descriptions of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Model-layers"

\end_inset

Layer description of the model.
 Conv are vanilla convolutions while Conv dw are depthwise separable convolution
s.
 We use batch normalization between layers and ReLU activation for all but
 the last Conv layer.
\end_layout

\end_inset


