\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to train our model in a self-supervised fashion, we need a way
 of applying the estimated homography onto the original image, 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{A}$
\end_inset

, to transform it to 
\begin_inset Formula $√é^{B}$
\end_inset

, which we can then compare with the original 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{B}$
\end_inset

.
 We would need two auxiliary layers: the Direct Linear Transform (DLT) layer
 and a Spatial Transformer layer.
 The DLT layer is responsible for transforming 
\begin_inset Formula $ƒ§_{4pt}$
\end_inset

, the 4-point homography output of the model, into 
\begin_inset Formula $‚Ñã(x_{i})$
\end_inset

, the 3√ó3 matrix parameterization, which is what we need to be able to compute
 point-to-point correspondences between images.
 On the other hand, the Spatial Transformer layer is for applying the estimated
 homography, 
\begin_inset Formula $‚Ñã(x_{i})$
\end_inset

, on the original image, 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{A}$
\end_inset

, to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $√é^{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The details on these layers will be tackled in the following subsections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the two auxiliary layers in place, we can now reframe the homography
 regression task as an image reconstruction task, thereby allowing us to
 use the input images themselves as the training targets, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Overview-of-training"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename model-train.png
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Overview-of-training"

\end_inset

Overview of training pipeline.
 We reframe the problem as an image reconstruction problem, similar to how
 autoencoders are trained.
 In addition to the image patches, we also use the full 320√ó240 source image
 as well as the patch corners.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the loss, we use an equally weighted combination of pixel-wise Mean
 Squared Error (MSE) and Structural Dissimilarity (DSSIM), as shown in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:total-loss"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{MSE}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^{n}(P^{A}(\text{‚Ñã}(x_{i}))-P^{B})^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
SSIM(x,y)=\frac{(2\mu_{x}\mu_{y}+c_{1})(2\sigma_{xy}+c_{2})}{(\mu_{x}^{2}+\mu_{y}^{2}+c_{1})(\sigma_{x}^{2}+\sigma_{y}^{2}+c_{2})}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{DSSIM}=\frac{1-SSIM(P^{A},P^{B})}{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{TOTAL}=L_{MSE}+L_{DSSIM}\label{eq:total-loss}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $ùúá_{x}$
\end_inset

 is the average of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

 is the covariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}=(k1L)^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}=(k2L)^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the dynamic range of the pixel values (typically 255), 
\begin_inset Formula $k1=0.01$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $k2=0.03$
\end_inset

 by default.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Direct Linear Transform Layer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a set of four 2D point correspondences 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\longleftrightarrow x'_{i}$
\end_inset

 we can determine the transformation matrix H that satisfies the equation
 
\begin_inset Formula $x'_{i}=Hx_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 However, for this equation involving homogeneous vectors, the 3-vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $x'_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Hx_{i}$
\end_inset

 may differ in magnitude by a non-zero scale factor.
 The vector cross product form of this equation can be expressed with the
 equation 
\begin_inset Formula $x'_{i}Hx_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 which allows us to derived 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 with a simple linear solution.
 Setting the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th row of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to be denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{jT}$
\end_inset

, then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Hx_{i}=\begin{pmatrix}h^{1T}x_{i}\\
h^{2T}x_{i}\\
h^{3T}x_{i}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}‚Äô_{i}=(x'_{i},y'_{i},w'_{i})^{T}$
\end_inset

, the cross product may then be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{0}^{T} & -w'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T} & y'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T}\\
w'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T} & \boldsymbol{0}^{T} & -x'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T}\\
-y'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T} & x'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T} & \boldsymbol{0}^{T}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}h^{1}\\
h^{2}\\
h^{3}
\end{pmatrix}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this equation, only two of them are linearly independent, thus, the 3rd
 equation can be omitted to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the equation above can be reduced to the form: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{0}^{T} & -w'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T} & y'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T}\\
w'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T} & \boldsymbol{0}^{T} & -x'_{i}\boldsymbol{x}_{i}^{T}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}h^{1}\\
h^{2}\\
h^{3}
\end{pmatrix}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}h=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a 2√ó9 matrix.
 With the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=(u_{i},v_{i},1)$
\end_inset

, then the equation above can be rewritten in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $√Ç_{i}ƒ•=b_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

 correspondence points.
 
\begin_inset Formula $√Ç_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 2√ó8 matrix of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{√Ç}_{\boldsymbol{i}}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 0 & 0 & -u_{i} & -v_{i} & -1 & v'_{i}u_{i} & v'_{i}v_{i}\\
u_{i} & v_{i} & 1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & -u'_{i}u_{i} & -u'_{i}v_{i}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 2-dim vector representing the last column of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{\boldsymbol{i}}$
\end_inset

 subtracted from both sides of the equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b_{i}}=[-v'_{i},u'_{i}]^{T}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{ƒ•}$
\end_inset

 as the first 8 elements of vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{h}$
\end_inset

.
 The equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A_{i}ƒ•}=\boldsymbol{b_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is differentiable and can solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{ƒ•}$
\end_inset

 by computing the pseudo inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{√Ç_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spatial Transformer Layer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This layer performs the homography transformation of an input image 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{A}$
\end_inset

 using the estimated 3√ó3 homography matrix derived from the DLT layer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inverse warping is performed to avoid holes in the warped image using the
 following 3 steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Computing the normalized inverse of the homography matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Creating a Parameterized Sampling Grid Generator (PSGG)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Performing a Differentiable Sampling (DS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step is simply computing the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $ƒ§$
\end_inset

 and with the normalized height and width coordinates of the images 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{B}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\leq u_{i},v_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\leq u'_{i},v'_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 The inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{ƒ§}_{inv}$
\end_inset

 can be computed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{ƒ§}_{inv}=M^{-1}ƒ§^{-1}M
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\begin{bmatrix}W'/2 & 0 & W'/2\\
0 & H'/2 & H'/2\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second step is to perform the inverse homography of each pixel in the
 second image 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{B}$
\end_inset

 to provide the pixel mapping to the first image 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{A}$
\end_inset

 with the following equation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}u_{i}\\
v_{i}\\
1
\end{bmatrix}=\text{‚Ñã}_{inv}(G_{i})=\boldsymbol{ƒ§}_{inv}\begin{bmatrix}u'_{i}\\
v'_{i}\\
1
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 3rd step is to produce a sample warped image 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of size 
\begin_inset Formula $H‚Äô$
\end_inset

√ó
\begin_inset Formula $W‚Äô$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 channels, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x_{i})=I^{A}(‚Ñã(x_{i}))$
\end_inset

.
 Using bilinear interpolation, the equation will be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{i}^{c}=\sum_{n}^{H}\sum_{m}^{W}I_{nm}^{c}max(0,1-|u_{i}-m|)max(0,1-|v_{i}-n|)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation is differentiable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and thus, can be used for the backpropagation of the loss functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We train our model for about 180,000 iterations at a batch size of 64 using
 the Adam optimizer with Nesterov momentum.
 On a test set of 50,000 samples, we get the results in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Our-model-achieves"

\end_inset

 which shows that our model improves upon the state-of-the-art by a significant
 margin.
\end_layout

