\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-estimated-homography"

\end_inset

, we visualize the predicted homography by using it to warp the first input
 image in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:input-image-1"

\end_inset

.
 We expect the warped version to look similar to the second input image
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:input-image-2"

\end_inset

.
 In this case, both models estimate a homography near the ground truth,
 thus making the warped images look similar to the second input image.
 However, upon closer inspection, we see that Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:warped-image-1"

\end_inset

 is actually closer to the ground truth than Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:warped-image-1-1"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we have shown the effectiveness of using a smaller but deeper
 fully convolutional network for homography estimation.
 We have also shown that a combination of MSE and Structural Dissimilarity
 objective functions are suitable for a self-supervised training setup.
 Our approach achieves higher accuracy while using much fewer parameters
 (3.4M vs 34M in the VGGNet-based models).
 We plan to extend our future work by benchmarking our results with real
 world datasets such as the aerial dataset performed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nguyen2018unsupervised"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

